<https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python-pandas-series-str-replace-to-replace-text-in-a-series/>

i thought i would give an example plus regex tips if you wanted to take it further

Example : if we wanted to change a column of age, stored as int, with the words, we could look for one value, eg 38, in that column and replace it like:
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(38, "thirty eight")`
another example, we want to remove the junk text that contains that pattern ‘38’ - lets say the string is
*“nearly38 years old”* 
we could use a regex pattern to identify all characters before the string ‘38’ and replace with nothing :
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(".*(38)", "")`
this returns *“years old”* because . finds any character and * allows you to take more than one character - that gives you all the letters up to 38, but includes 38.
adding a ?= makes the pattern  what we can call un greedy - so take all characters up to 38 but dont steal 38:
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(".*(?=38)", "")`
this returns *“38 years old”*
<https://cheatography.com/davechild/cheat-sheets/regular-expressions/>

Create a new column called `Combo Type` whose value combines `Type 1` and `Type 2`.
Rules:
• If both `Type 1` and `Type 2` have valid values, the `Combo Type` value should contain both values in the form of `<Type 1> <Type 2>`. For example, if `Type 1` value is `Grass` and `Type 2` value is `Poison`, `Combo Type` will be `Grass-Poison`.
• If `Type 1` has valid value but `Type 2` is not, `Combo Type` will be the same as `Type 1`. For example, if `Type 1` is `Fire` whereas `Type 2` is `NaN`, `Combo Type` will be `Fire`.
